{"timestamp": "2025-12-07 03:45:13.966292", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nSummary of current state\n- End-to-end functionality from client_0 to the pod0 service web0.pod0 (10.0.1.2) is working:\n  - DNS resolution: OK (web0.pod0 → 10.0.1.2 via dns_pod0 10.0.0.2).\n  - HTTP reachability: OK (curl exit code 0; low latency).\n  - ICMP reachability: OK (client_0 → 10.0.1.2 with 0% loss, ~1–3 ms).\n- Fabric control plane looks healthy:\n  - All eBGP sessions on leaf_router_0_0 and leaf_router_0_1 are up to all four upstream neighbors (spines), with routes learned and ECMP installed for expected service /24s.\n- Data-plane fabric appears healthy:\n  - Broad cross-host ping tests show 0% packet loss and low RTTs across many pod subnets.\n\nDetected anomaly\n- Deviation from design: leaf_router_0_1 is originating and advertising a more-specific 10.0.1.0/25 in addition to the planned aggregate 10.0.1.0/24 for pod0 idx1.\n  - Evidence:\n    - leaf_router_0_1 running config:\n      - interface lo ip address 10.0.1.0/25\n      - router bgp 65201: network 10.0.1.0/24 and network 10.0.1.0/25\n    - leaf_router_0_1 BGP RIB shows 10.0.1.0/25 as locally sourced and best (weight 32768).\n    - leaf_router_0_0 BGP sees 10.0.1.0/25 from all four spines, and installs it alongside the 10.0.1.0/24 (consistent propagation of the more-specific).\n  - This is not aligned with the described design (“each leaf advertises one service subnet 10.<pod>.<idx>.0/24”).\n\nAdditional observations relevant to the anomaly\n- On leaf_router_0_1, the Linux kernel FIB (ip route) shows 10.0.1.0/24 via eth4 (correct), but no 10.0.1.0/25 via lo is listed in the FIB dump we retrieved. FRR’s RIB, however, lists C>* 10.0.1.0/25 via lo. The current FIB state is allowing proper forwarding to 10.0.1.2 via eth4 (confirmed by successful client pings and HTTP).\n- BGP summary counts differ slightly between leaves (leaf_router_0_0 shows 36 prefixes received per neighbor while leaf_router_0_1 shows 35). This is consistent with the presence of an extra more-specific route in the fabric and asymmetric reception of prefixes across nodes, but does not presently indicate a session or reachability failure.\n\nLocalization of the issue\n- Device: leaf_router_0_1\n- Interfaces/objects involved:\n  - Loopback (lo) configured with 10.0.1.0/25\n  - BGP configuration advertising both 10.0.1.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/25\n\nRoot cause assessment\n- Misconfiguration on leaf_router_0_1:\n  - A subnet address (10.0.1.0/25) has been assigned to the loopback and actively advertised in BGP as a more-specific route in addition to the intended 10.0.1.0/24. This deviates from the documented design (aggregated /24 per leaf) and introduces an inconsistent control-plane state.\n  - Potential side effects of this misconfiguration (even if not currently observed):\n    - Unintended traffic steering to leaf_router_0_1 for all 10.0.1.0/25 destinations.\n    - Risk of local blackholing if the kernel FIB installs and prefers the connected /25 to lo over the /24 to eth4 (longest-prefix match), which would sink traffic for 10.0.1.0–10.0.1.127 to the loopback device rather than forwarding to the actual service subnet. Current tests suggest this is not happening at the moment, but the risk exists because the control-plane advertises the more-specific.\n\nNon-issues/normal findings\n- dns_pod0: Bind is listening on 10.0.0.2:53; DNS responds correctly.\n- webserver0_pod0: Python HTTP server is listening on 0.0.0.0:80; reachable and serving content.\n- eBGP sessions: All neighbors up on both leafs; routes present; ECMP paths established for expected /24s.\n- The “unknown” reachability status shown for webserver0_pod0 in the bulk test appears to be due to sampling limitations rather than a connectivity failure (direct tests confirm it is accessible).\n\nOverall assessment\n- Fabric health: Generally healthy (control-plane sessions stable, data-plane forwarding functioning).\n- Anomaly: Configuration non-compliance on leaf_router_0_1 (unintended 10.0.1.0/25 advertisement from loopback) that could lead to future forwarding anomalies or blackholing under different FIB conditions.\n- Current user-impact: None observed during tests (DNS and HTTP for web0.pod0 are working with low latency).", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 24824, "output_tokens": 5580, "total_tokens": 30404, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 21504}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 4416}}}
